          }}>{`encodeURIComponent`}</code></a>{`. This is a standard JavaScript function that encodes special characters in a URI, preventing a possible injection attack vector.`}</p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>{`For a simple example, suppose our REST endpoint responded to the following URLs:`}</p>
    <ul>
      <li parentName="ul">{`DELETE `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`/movies/:id`}</code></li>
      <li parentName="ul">{`DELETE `}<code parentName="li" {...{
          "className": "language-text"
        }}>{`/movies/:id/characters`}</code></li>
    </ul>
    <p>{`A "malicious" client could provide an `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`:id`}</code>{` of `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`1/characters`}</code>{` to target the delete `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`characters`}</code>{` endpoint when it was the singular `}<code parentName="p" {...{
        "className": "language-text"
      }}>{`movie`}</code>{` endpoint that we were trying to delete. URI encoding prevents this kind of injection by transforming the `}<code parentName="p" {...{
